user.biography: Sharing photos of #Harvard on campus and around the world.

node.accessibility_caption: A woman stands outside in front of stone steps to a brick building

node.text:
Recent HBS graduate Cathy Chukwulebe launched Little Black Library in 2020. The idea is similar to little free libraries, but with the mission to promote discussions of the Black experience through literature.⠀
⠀
"Our hope is that discussing these topics through literature can create a space where uncomfortable conversations are welcomed in a way that can help us grow together," said Cathy. "It's pretty easy and inviting to talk about a book."⠀
⠀
Little Black Libraries are popping up nationwide, and one of the newest is at Harvard Business School's Baker Library. Check out our Story for more info.

node.accessibility_caption: A person wearing a white lab coat works on a very large computer with gears and wires exposed

node.text:
The Mark I, one of the world’s first programmable computers, was 50 feet long and weighed 5 tons. Designed by Harvard mathematician Howard Aiken in 1937, the enormous computer landed at Harvard in 1944. It recently moved from the Science Center to the new Science and Engineering Complex. Check out our Story to see more.⠀
⠀
#Harvard ⠀
⠀
Photo: @Rosie_Lincoln/Harvard Staff Photographer
